<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900827-0023</DOCNO><DOCID>900827-0023.</DOCID><HL>   Bush Discusses '91 Budget   In Light of Events in Gulf</HL><DATE>08/27/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A12</SO><IN>ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)</IN><GV>EXECUTIVE (EXE)TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)</GV><LP>   WASHINGTON -- President Bush met with his top economicadvisers to discuss the fiscal 1991 budget in light of recentevents in the Persian Gulf, administration officials said.   The meeting, which included Treasury Secretary NicholasBrady, Budget Director Richard Darman and White House Chiefof Staff John Sununu, focused on the proposed mix of spendingcuts for fiscal 1991, when the administration is pledged toshrink the federal deficit by $50 billion. It is widelyexpected that cuts in defense spending may now be smallerthan originally planned because of Iraq's Aug. 2 invasion ofKuwait and the subsequent deployment of U.S. forces in theregion.</LP><TEXT>   &quot;It was a planning session, they're going to be gettingtogether later, in September,&quot; an administration officialsaid after the meeting, which was held in Kennebunkport,Maine, where the president is spending his summer vacation.   &quot;The administration remains firm and resolute that abudget agreement is critical,&quot; this official said, addingthat the proposed $50 billion of savings for fiscal 1991,which begins Oct. 1, is &quot;still a fairly firm number.&quot;   Meanwhile, President Bush signed the paperwork needed toauthorize the Office of Management and Budget to carry outthe automatic spending cuts required under the Gramm-Rudmandeficit-reduction act. The presidential order specifies thatthe automatic spending restraints take effect Oct. 1.</TEXT></DOC>